{{use dmy dates|date=April 2019}} {{Infobox person |name = Maria Swanenburg |image = Maria Swanenburg.jpg |image_size = |birth_name = {{nowr|Maria Catherina Swanenburg}} |birth_date = {{birth date|1839|09|09|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Leiden]], Netherlands |death_date = {{death date and age|1915|04|11|1839|09|09|df=y}} |death_place = [[Gorinchem]], Netherlands |other_names = "Goeie Mie" |module = {{Infobox|child=yes |header1 = Criminal details |label2 = Motive |data2 = Life insurance payout |label3 = Method |data3 = [[Arsenic poisoning]] |label4 = Victims |data4 = 27 confirmed, suspect to be over 90 victims |label5 = Crime span |data5 = 1880–1883 |label6 = Apprehended |data6 = December 1883 |label7 = Conviction |data7 = Murder (× 3) |label8 = Sentence |data8 = [[Life imprisonment]]}} }}
'''Maria Catherina van der Linden-Swanenburg''' (9 September 1839&nbsp;– 11 April 1915) was a Dutch [[serial killer]] who murdered at least 27 people and was suspected of killing more than 90 people.
== Early life == Maria Swanenburg was the daughter of Clemens Swanenburg and Johanna Dingjan. After Maria's first two daughters died at a young age, she married Johannes van der Linden on 13 May 1868. The result of this marriage was five sons and two daughters. The marriage lasted until 29 January 1886.{{sfn|Moerman|2013|loc=§&nbsp;1}}
Her nickname was "Goeie Mie" (Good Mie), which she received because of her amicable neighborly assistance in babysitting and taking care of the sick and elderly in [[Leiden]]'s poor neighborhood, where she herself lived.{{sfn|Rasovich|1995|loc=§&nbsp;17}}{{sfn|Weterings|2019|loc=§&nbsp;3}}
== Murders == Her first victim was her own mother, in 1880; not long thereafter she poisoned her father as well.
It was established with certainty that at least 102 people were [[arsenic poisoning|poisoned with arsenic]] between 1880 and 1883. Twenty-seven of her victims were killed,{{sfn|Rasovich|1995|loc=§&nbsp;8}} of whom 16 were her relatives.{{sfn|Rasovich|1995|loc=§&nbsp;9}} The investigation included more than 90 suspicious deaths.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} Forty-five survivors sustained chronic health issues after having ingested the poison.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}
Swanenburg's motive was the payout of her victims' insurance or their inheritance. She had secured most of the insurance policies herself.{{sfn|Weterings|2019|loc=§&nbsp;4}}
=== Capture and imprisonment === Swanenburg was caught after she poisened the Frankhuizen family in December 1883.{{sfn|Weterings|2019|loc=§&nbsp;5}} Her trial began on 23 April 1885.{{sfn|Moerman|2013|loc=§&nbsp;3}} Swanenburg was found guilty of having killed at least three victims and she was sentenced to life imprisonment in a correctional facility, where she died in 1915.{{sfn|Weterings|2019|loc=§&nbsp;8}}
