ew that he acted on behalf of foreign interests in the Balkans that benefited from the king's murder. «Immediately after the murder, the city was in uproar and rumors offered by Greeks blamed the scapegoats of the time, the Turks and Bulgarians. But more persistent rumors spoke of a German plan to liquidate the pro-English king in order to promote German interests in Greece,» Zafeiris writes. «One version, considered more likely than the rest, has it that the king was the victim of German diplomacy given that George's policy ran counter to German plans for the Balkans and Eastern Europe. The German rulers themselves wanted the pro-German successor Constantine, who identified with German policy in Greece, at the head of the Greek state.» The death of Schinas, who fell or was pushed out of a window at the military headquarters where he was being held, lent force to rumors and speculation about the real cause of the murder. | ref={{harvid | Kathimerini | 2006}} | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210041932/http://www.ekathimerini.com/45572/article/ekathimerini/news/four-famous-targets-of-assassination-in-salonica | archivedate=2018-12-09 | url-status=live}} * {{Cite book |last1=Kemp |first1=Michael |chapter=Beneath a White Tower |title=Bombs, Bullets and Bread: The Politics of Anarchist Terrorism Worldwide, 1866–1926 |pages=178–186 |year=2018 |isbn=978-1-4766-7101-7 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company|McFarland]] |location=Jefferson, North Carolina |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=J7VqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT178 |ref=harv }} * {{Citation |last=Magrini |title=The King's Assassin Explains Himself to the Journalist Magrini |date=March 1913 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J7VqDwAAQBAJ |work=Aionos |access-date=2018-12-08 |translator-last=Fragkos |translator-first=Grigorios | ref=harv}} as published in {{harvnb | Kemp | 2018 | pp=184–186}} * {{Cite book |last=Mattox | first=Henry E. | date=2015-06-08 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XofeCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA22 | title=Chronology of World Terrorism, 1901–2001 | publisher=McFarland | isbn=9781476609652 | language=en | ref=harv | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210042440/https://books.google.com/books?id=XofeCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA22 | archivedate=2018-12-09 | url-status=live}} * {{Cite news |work=The National Herald |date=2017-06-21 |title=The Assassination of King George – March, 1913 |url=https://www.thenationalherald.com/167025/assassination-king-george-march-1913/ |access-date=2018-12-09 |language=en-US | ref={{harvid | The National Herald | 2017}} | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210042442/https://www.thenationalherald.com/167025/assassination-king-george-march-1913/ | archivedate=2018-12-09 | url-status=live}} * ''The New York Times'' :a. {{Cite news |work=The New York Times | date=1913-03-19 | title=King of Greece murdered at Salonika; slayer mad; political results feared | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1913/03/19/104910497.pdf | access-date=2018-12-02 | agency=Marconi Transaltantic Wireless Telegraph | ref={{harvid | The New York Times | 1913}}}} :b. {{Cite news |work=The New York Times | date=2013-03-19 | title=Died before reaching hospital | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1913/03/19/104910498.pdf | access-date=2018-12-02 | ref={{harvid | The New York Times | 1913b}}}} :c. {{Cite news |work=The New York Times | date=2013-03-20 | title=The assassin lived here | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1913/03/20/100611826.pdf | access-date=2018-12-02 | ref={{harvid | The New York Times | 1913c}}}} :d. {{Cite news |work=The New York Times | date=1913-03-20 | title=King's Murderer is Educated Anarchist | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1913/03/20/100611820.pdf | access-date=2018-12-02 | agency=Marconi Transatlantic Wireless Telegraph | ref={{harvid | The New York Times | 1913d}}}} :e. {{Cite news |work=The New York Times | date=1913-03-20 | title=King's murderer is educated anarchist