{{Infobox person | name = Issei Sagawa | image_caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|04|26}} | birth_place = [[Kobe]], [[Japan]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Japan]]ese | occupation = Writer | height = 1.45 m | criminal_charge= Attempted murder, cannibalism.(falsely identified as attempted rape by officials) {{small|(Japan)}} | criminal_status= Unfit to stand trial by reason of insanity | module = {{Infobox |child=yes | label16 = | data16 = | label17 = Date | data17 = June 11, 1981
| label21 = {{nowrap|Location}} | data21 = [[Paris]], [[France]] | label25 = {{nowrap|Weapon}} | data25 = Hunting Rifle }} }}
{{Nihongo|'''Issei Sagawa'''|佐川 一政|Sagawa Issei|extra=born April 26, 1949}},<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.learning-history.com/issei-sagawa/|title=Issei Sagawa: Cannibal Killer|website=Learning History|accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref> also known as '''Pang''', is a Japanese man who, while living in [[Paris]] in 1981, killed and [[cannibal]]ized a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] woman. He was released after two years of pre-trial detention upon being found [[legally insane]].
==Early life== Sagawa was born in [[Kobe]], [[Hyōgo Prefecture]], Japan, to wealthy parents. He was born prematurely, reportedly small enough to fit in the palm of his father's hand, and immediately developed [[enteritis]], a disease of the small intestine. He eventually recovered after several injections of potassium and calcium in saline.<ref name=nc/>
Sagawa first experienced cannibalistic desires while in the first grade, after seeing a male's thigh.<ref name="vice"/> In a 2011 interview with ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', Sagawa reported that as a youth he partook in [[bestiality]] with his dog and experienced cannibalistic desires for women.<ref name="vicevid"/>
At 24, in [[Tokyo]], Sagawa followed a tall German woman home, then broke into her apartment while she was sleeping with intent to cannibalize her by slicing off part of her buttocks and sneaking away with a small part of her flesh. She awoke and, Sagawa claims, pushed him to the ground. He was captured by police and charged with attempted rape. He did not confess his true intentions to authorities.<ref name="vicevid">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BosZxa1bYcE|title=Interview with a Cannibal|work=Vice Magazine}}</ref>
In 1977, at the age of 27, Sagawa moved to France to pursue a Ph.D. in literature at the [[Paris-Sorbonne University|Sorbonne]] in Paris.<ref name=nc/> He has said that while residing in Paris, "Almost every night I would bring a prostitute home and then try to shoot them, but for some reason my fingers froze up and I couldn't pull the trigger."<ref name="vice">{{cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/read/whos-hungry-502-v16n1|title=Who's Hungry?|last=Kosuga|first=Tomokazu|author2=Lena Oishi, Lena|date=January 1, 2009 |work=Vice Magazine}}</ref>
==Killing of Hartevelt== On June 11, 1981, Sagawa, then 32, invited his Sorbonne classmate Renée Hartevelt to dinner at his apartment at 10 Rue Erlanger, under the pretext of translating poetry for a school assignment. He planned to kill and eat her, having selected her for her health and beauty - characteristics he felt he lacked. Sagawa considered himself weak, ugly, and small (he is 1.448&nbsp;m (4&nbsp;ft 9&nbsp;in) tall)<ref name="Ramsland">{{cite web |url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/weird/sagawa/1.html?sect=3 |title=The Cannibal Celebrity: Issei Sagawa |first=Katherine |last=Ramsland |publisher=[[TruTV]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717083659/http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/serial_killers/weird/sagawa/1.html?sect=3 |archivedate=July 17, 2009}}</ref> and claims he wanted to absorb her energy. She was 25 years old and 1.78 m (5&nbsp;ft 10 in).<ref name="Luzajic">{{cite web|url=http://www.gremolata.com/Articles/571-The-Sweetest-Taboo-An-Anthropology-of-Anthropophagy.aspx |title=The Sweetest Taboo: An Anthropology of Anthropophagy |last=Luzajic |first=Lorette C. |publisher=Gremolata|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125235315/http://www.gremolata.com/Articles/571-The-Sweetest-Taboo-An-Anthropology-of-Anthropophagy.aspx|archivedate=January 25, 2010}}</ref> After she arrived, she began reading poetry at a desk with her back to him. He shot her in the neck with a rifle. Sagawa said he fainted after the shock of shooting her, but awoke with the realization that he had to carry out his plan.<ref name=nc/> He had [[Necrophilia|sex with her corpse]] but he could not bite into her skin because his teeth were not sharp enough, so he left the apartment and purchased a butcher knife.<ref name=nc>{{cite journal|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=September 20, 2007|title=Issei Sagawa: Celebrity Cannibal|journal=New Criminologist, the On-line Journal of Criminology|publisher=New Criminologist|url=http://www.newcriminologist.com/article.asp?nid=17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714172725/http://www.newcriminologist.com/article.asp?nid=17|archivedate=July 14, 2011 }}</ref> Sagawa ate various parts of her body, eating most of her breasts and face, saving other parts in his refrigerator. He also took photographs of her at each eating stage.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lexpress.fr/actualite/societe/fait-divers/incendie-suicide-cannibalisme-a-paris-la-rue-erlanger-est-maudite_2061065.html |title=Incendie, suicide, cannibalism: la maudite rue Erlanger |newspaper=L'Express |language=French |date=February 6, 2019 }}</ref> He then attempted to dump her body in a lake in the [[Bois de Boulogne]], but was seen in the act and arrested by French police.<ref name=nc/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/asiapcf/12/07/vbs.japanese.cannibal/|title=Murderer, cannibal, celebrity: Inside the mind of Issei Sagawa|website=Cnn.com|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref> When he was caught, he was carrying two suitcases. Those suitcases contained the dismembered body parts of Renée Hartevelt.
Sagawa's wealthy father provided a lawyer for his defense, and after being held for two years awaiting trial Sagawa was found [[Insanity defence |legally insane]] and unfit to stand trial by the French judge, [[Jean-Louis Bruguière]], who ordered him held indefinitely in a mental institution.<ref name=nc/> After a visit by the author [[Inuhiko Yomota]], Sagawa's account of his kill was published in Japan under the title ''In the Fog''.<ref name=nc/> Sagawa's subsequent publicity and macabre celebrity likely contributed to the French authorities' decision to deport him to Japan, where he was immediately committed to Matsuzawa hospital. Examining psychologists there all declared him sane and found sexual perversion was his sole motivation for murder.<ref name=nc/> Because charges in France had been dropped, the French court documents were sealed and were not released to Japanese authorities; consequently Sagawa could not legally be detained in Japan. He checked himself out of the hospital on August 12, 1986, and remains free.<ref name=nc/> Sagawa's continued freedom has been widely criticized.<ref name=nc/>
==Post-release== Between 1986 and 1997 he was frequently invited to be a guest speaker and commentator.<ref name="Ref_">Kushner, Barak. (1997). "Cannibalizing Japanese Media: The Case of Issei Sagawa". Journal of Popular Culture, vol. 31 (3), p.&nbsp;55-57</ref> In 1992, he appeared in [[Hisayasu Sato]]'s exploitation film ''Uwakizuma: Chijokuzeme (Unfaithful Wife: Shameful Torture)''<!--the original title; "the bedroom" doesn't quite catch the plot--> as a sado-sexual voyeur.<ref name=imdb>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0756028/ |title=Issei Sagawa |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=September 26, 2009}}</ref> Sagawa has written books about the murder he committed, as well as ''Shonen A'', a book on the 1997 [[Kobe child murders]].<ref name="Books">[https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/2795905 Issei Sagawa] at [[Goodreads]]</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=November 2018|sure=yes}} He has also written restaurant reviews for the Japanese magazine ''Spa''.<ref name="Ref_a">Henshall, Kenneth G. ''Dimensions of Japanese society: gender, margins and mainstream''. rev.ed. Palgrave Macmillan, London 1999 p.207</ref> Sagawa can no longer find publishers for his writing and he has struggled to find employment. He was nearly accepted by a French-language school because the manager was impressed by his courage in using his real name, but employees protested and he was rejected.
In 2005 Sagawa's parents died. He was prevented from attending their funeral, but repaid their creditors and moved into public housing. He received welfare benefits for a time.<ref>『週刊新潮』2006年2月23日号。</ref> In an interview with [[Vice Magazine|''Vice'' magazine]] in 2011, he said that being forced to make a living while being known as a murderer and cannibal was a terrible punishment.<ref name="vice" /> In 2013 he was hospitalized from a [[cerebral infarction]] which permanently damaged his nervous system. Since being released he has been under the full-time care of his brother. {{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}
==In popular culture== * Three documentary films featuring Sagawa have been produced: ''Excuse Me for Living'' ([[Channel 4]], UK, 1993, 60 minutes); ''The Cannibal That Walked Free'' ([[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]], UK, 2007, 46 minutes) and ''Interview with a Cannibal'' (''Vice'', US, 2011, 34 minutes). * A 1986 short film by Olivier Smolders, ''Adoration'', is based on Sagawa's story,<ref name="Knoll">{{cite web|url=http://metrotimes.com/editorial/story.asp?id=10425|title=Bard of Brooklyn|last=Knoll|first=Paul|date=April 25, 2007|newspaper=[[Metro Times]]|accessdate=September 26, 2009}}</ref> as is a 1986 short documentary, ''Cannibal Superstar'', released by the TV channel [[Viasat Explorer]]. ''VBS Meets: Issei Sagawa'', a short documentary about him, aired on [[VBS.tv]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/exabep/vbs-meets-issei-sagawa|title=VICE MEETS ISSEI SAGAWA|website=Vice|date=November 18, 2010|accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref> * "[[Too Much Blood]]", a song on the [[Rolling Stones]]' 1983 album ''[[Undercover (The Rolling Stones album)|Undercover]]'', is about Sagawa and violence in the media. His crime also inspired [[the Stranglers]]' 1981 song "[[La Folie (song)|La Folie]]". The [[Noise metal|Noise]] [[Black Metal]] band [[Gnaw Their Tongues]] also released an EP titled ''[[Issei Sagawa (EP)|Issei Sagawa]]'' in 2006. * Sagawa's crimes, and his later career as an actor, were discussed in the 2015 documentary ''[[Fear Itself (film)|Fear Itself]]'' by filmmaker [[Charlie Lyne]]. * Verena Paravel and Lucien Castaing-Taylor co-produced a film about Sagawa called ''Caniba'', which was shown at the 2017 Venice and Toronto International Film Festivals to mixed reviews from the public.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Guy|last=Lodge|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/caniba-review-1202563494/|title=Film Review: 'Caniba'|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=September 19, 2017|accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref>
